"Joshi U.D., Joshi P.N., Roh H.S., Yoon W.L., Shiralkar V.P.","Environmental potential applications of alkali metal exchanged zeolite x in carbon dioxide adsorption",2011,"Research Journal of Chemistry and Environment","15","2",,"661","671",,,,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-80051866537&partnerID=40&md5=66616cf9e07e418d9118e928c82b956e","Netaji Subhash Chandra Bose College, Nanded, India; Catalysis Division, National Chemical Laboratory, Pune, India; Strategic Technology Research Division, Korea Institute of Energy Research, Daejeon 305-343, South Korea; Department of Environmental Engineering, Yonsei University, 234, Maeji, Heungeop, Gwangwon-do 220-710, South Korea","Joshi, U.D., Netaji Subhash Chandra Bose College, Nanded, India; Joshi, P.N., Catalysis Division, National Chemical Laboratory, Pune, India; Roh, H.S., Department of Environmental Engineering, Yonsei University, 234, Maeji, Heungeop, Gwangwon-do 220-710, South Korea; Yoon, W.L., Strategic Technology Research Division, Korea Institute of Energy Research, Daejeon 305-343, South Korea; Shiralkar, V.P., Catalysis Division, National Chemical Laboratory, Pune, India","The increasing atmospheric CO 2 concentration, mainly caused by the Thermal Power Stations, Industrial sector and fossil fuel combustion, has led to consequences of global warming. Zeolitic adsorption processes is more promising, energy saving and viable method for CO 2 removal in comparison to other technologies. In order to examine the behavior and to establish the trends in carbon dioxide sorption, NaXzeolite (Si/Al = 1.15) and it's the modified forms with identical degree (55.5 ± 2.5) of exchange by K+, Rb+ andCs+ cations have been selected. The samples were characterized by powder XRD, Low temperature nitrogen adsorption/desorption measurements, chemical analysis and also for the intermediate electronegativity and the partial charges on the atoms using Sanderson's electronegativity equalization principle. The isotherms of carbon dioxide using these NaX, NaKX, NaRbX and NaCsX samples were measured at an interval of 30 K in the temperature range of 273 to 363 K up to 600 Torr. The uptake of CO 2 was found to depend on both, the size of the nonframework cation and the temperature at which the isotherms were measured. The cations with lower charge density will have lower extent of electrostatic interaction with the sorbate molecules. Since CO 2 has more linear quadrupole moment, it interacts mainly with the extra-framework cations and framework oxygen. The carbon dioxide sorption data satisfactorily represented by Langmuir and also analyzed for the chemical affinity. The Isosteric heat (q st) of NaX for the coverage of 20 molecules per unit cell is nearly equal to 26 kJ, mol-1. The NaX and NaKX comparatively show aflat heat profile with the increasing amount sorbed than those of NaRbX and NaCsX indicating a balance between the strength of energetic heterogeneity of sorbate-sorbent interactions and sorbate-sorbate interactions.","CO 2 sorption; Ionic exchange; Isosteric heat; NaX zeolite; Theoretical models","adsorption; alkalinity; carbon dioxide; cation; combustion; concentration (composition); desorption; energy conservation; fossil fuel; global warming; heterogeneity; ion exchange; isotherm; low temperature; measurement method; metal; molecular analysis; numerical model; oxygen; power plant; sorption; thermal power; X-ray diffraction; zeolite",,,,,,"Amari, D., Lopez Cuesta, J.M., Nguyen, N.P., Jerrentrup, R., Ginoux, J.L., (1992) Therm. Anal, 38, p. 1005; Barrer, R.M., Gibbons, R.M., (1965) Trans. Faraday Soc., 61, p. 948; Breck, D.W., (1974) Zeolite Molecular Sieves Wiley, , New York, Chapter 2; Burevski, D., Pilchowski, K., Bergk, K.H., (1991) Croat. Chem. Acta, 64, p. 199; Calero, S., Dubbeldam, D., Krishna, R., Smit, B., Vlugt, T.J.H., Denayer, J.F.M., Martens, J.A., Maesen, T.L.M., (2004) J. Am. Chem. Soc., 124, p. 11377; Choudhary, V.R., Mayadevi, S., Singh, A.P., (1995) J. Chem. Soc. Faraday Trans. I, 91, p. 2935; Coughlan, B., McEntee, J., (1976) J. Proc. Roy. Irish Acad., 76 B, p. 191; Coughlan, B., Kilmartin, S., (1975) J. Chem. Soc. Faraday Trans. I., 71, p. 1809; Coughlanand, B., Kilmartin, S., (1975) J.C.S. Faraday Trans I., 71, p. 1809; Barthmeuf, D., (2003) Micropor Mesopor Mater, 66, p. 1; Go, A.J., Sholl, D.S., Akten, E.D., Kohen, D., (2002) J. Phys. Chem. B., 106, p. 8367; Haq, N., Ruthven, D.M., (1986) J. Colloid Interface Sci., 112, p. 154; Haq, N., Ruthven, D.M., (1986) J. Colloid Interface Sci., 112, p. 164; Jeong, S.Y., Jin, H., Lee, J.M., Yim, D.J., (2001) Micropor Mesopor Mater, 44-45, p. 717; Joshi, P.N., Kim, T.H., Kim, K.I., Shiralkar, V.P., (1999) Adsorp. Sci. Technol., 17 (8), p. 639; Joshi, U.D., Joshi, P.N., Tamhankar, S.S., Joshi, V.V., Shiralkar, V.P., (2001) J. Phy. Chem. B., 105, p. 10637; Joshi, U.D., Joshi, P.N., Tamhankar, S.S., Joshi, V.V., Shiralkar, V.V., (2001) J. Colloid Interface Sci., 235, p. 135; Khelifa, A., Derriche, Z., Bengueddach, A., (1999) App. Catal. A. General, 178, p. 61; Khvoschev, S.S., Zhdanov, S.P., Belotserkovskii, G.M., Redin, V.I., (1968) Russ. J. Phy. Chem., 42, p. 82; Khvoshchev, S.S., Zverev, A.V., (1991) Zeolites, 11, p. 742; Krista, S., (2006) Micro and Mesoporous Materials, 91, p. 78; Maurin, G., Llewellyn, P., Poyet, T., Kuchta, B., (2005) J. Phys. Chem.B., 109, p. 125; Maurin, G., Llewellyn, P.L., Bell, R.G., (2005) J. Phys. Chem. B., 109, p. 16084; Pires, J., Decarvalho, M.B., Ribeiro, F.R., Derouane, E.G., (1993) J. Mol. Catal., 85, p. 295; Sanderson, R.T., (1983) J. Am. Chem. Soc, 105 (8), p. 2259; Sidorenko, Y.N., Galich, P.N., Gutyrya, V.S., Il'In, V.G., Neimark, I.E., (1967) Dokl. Akad. Nauk SSSR, 173, p. 132; Siriwardane, R.V., Shen, M.S., Fisher, E.P., Poston, J.A., (2001) Energy Fuels, 15, p. 279; VanBekkum, H., Flanigen, E.M., Jacobs, P.A., (2001) J. Stud Surf. Sci. Catal., 137; Vasil'eva, E.A., Khvoshchev, S.S., Karetina, I.V., (1984) Izv. Akad. Nauk SSSR Ser.